initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent years, recurrent self-modifying automata (RSMA) have been applied for sequence prediction successfully. quantum recurrent self-modifying automata (QRSMA) are proposed as a novel generalization to RSMA by using quantum entanglement mechanisms. The quantum entanglement leads to an efficient search process in QRSMA by reducing the size of search space from O(2^n) to O(n). This paper implements and compares both RSMA and QRSMA by testing validation metrics and prediction accuracy on three commonly used sequence datasets. The datasets include music genres, language translation and biological pathways. Additionally, uncertainty quantification (UQ), a technique commonly used in RSMA to improve the performance of forecasting by generating robust predictions, is also implemented in QRSMA. Surprisingly, the results showed that uncertainty quantification didn't improve QRSMA performance. The reasons and implications behind this result are analyzed, seeking to deepen our understanding of quantum artificial life theory.

In recent years, hyper-dimensional meta-forecasters have been deployed for large-scale climate modeling with commendable results. Quantum meta-forecasters are proposed as a novel advancement to hyper-dimensional forecasting by leveraging non-locality correlations. Non-locality enables a remarkably swift search process in quantum meta-forecasters, contracting the search space from O(3^n) to O(log n). This research juxtaposes both hyper-dimensional and quantum meta-forecasters by evaluating their respective validation metrics and accuracy on four renowned atmospheric datasets. The datasets encompass temperature fluctuations, atmospheric pressures, and ozone layer dynamics. Moreover, probabilistic modeling, a standard technique in climatology to bolster predictive resilience, is also integrated with quantum meta-forecasters. Astonishingly, the experiments demonstrated that probabilistic modeling had an unforeseen detrimental impact on quantum meta-forecasters' accuracy. The findings are subject to in-depth analysis, endeavoring to clarify the enigmatic connection between quantum physics and high-performance computing in global climate modeling.
